{"title_page": "Razan Taha", "text_new": "{{short description|Jordanian swimmer}}\n'''Razan Taha''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0632\u0627\u0646 \u0637\u0647}}; born December 29, 1991) is a Jordanian swimmer, who specialized in sprint freestyle events.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Razan Taha|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ta/razan-taha-1.html|18 December 2012}}</ref> She represented her nation [[Jordan]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], placing herself among the top 70 swimmers in the 50 m freestyle.\n\nAt age sixteen, Taha became one of the youngest swimmers to mark their debut for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], competing in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|women's 50 m freestyle]]. She raced to fourth in heat five with a time of 27.82, just a close, hundredth-second margin (0.010 behind top three finisher [[Dalia T\u00f3rrez Zamora]] of Nicaragua. Taha, however, failed to advance into the semi-finals, as she placed fifty-sixth overall out of ninety-two swimmers in the prelims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 50m Freestyle \u2013 Heat 5|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc=SWW010900/index.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=18 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120821062506/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSWW010900/index.html|archivedate=21 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=64449/bio/index.html NBC 2008 Olympics profile] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taha, Razan}}\n[[Category:Jordanian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Jordan]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Female freestyle swimmers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Amman]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n\n\n{{Jordan-swimming-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Jordanian swimmer}}\n'''Razan Taha''' ({{lang-ar|\u0631\u0632\u0627\u0646 \u0637\u0647}}; born December 29, 1991) is a Jordanian swimmer, who specialized in sprint freestyle events.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|Razan Taha|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ta/razan-taha-1.html|18 December 2012}}</ref> She represented her nation [[Jordan]] at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]], placing herself among the top 70 swimmers in the 50 m freestyle.\n\nAt age sixteen, Taha became one of the youngest swimmers to mark their debut for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], competing in the [[Swimming at the 2008 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's 50 metre freestyle|women's 50 m freestyle]]. She raced to fourth in heat five with a time of 27.82, just a close, hundredth-second margin (0.010 behind top three finisher [[Dalia T\u00f3rrez Zamora]] of Nicaragua. Taha, however, failed to advance into the semi-finals, as she placed fifty-sixth overall out of ninety-two swimmers in the prelims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Women's 50m Freestyle \u2013 Heat 5|url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc=SWW010900/index.html|publisher=[[NBC Olympics]]|accessdate=18 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120821062506/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/swimming/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSWW010900/index.html|archivedate=21 August 2012}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=64449/bio/index.html NBC Olympics Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taha, Razan}}\n[[Category:Jordanian female swimmers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Jordan]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Female freestyle swimmers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Amman]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n\n{{Jordan-swimming-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "tag dead link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Razan_Taha"}
{"title_page": "Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area \n| name = Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Barra del Colorado Waterway.jpg\n| photo_caption =\n| location = [[Costa Rica]]\n| map = Costa Rica\n| nearest_city = \n| coordinates = {{coords|10|46|18|N|83|35|56|W|display=inline, title}}\n| area = 200,600 acres (812 km\u00b2)\n| established = 1984\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = National System of Conservation Areas ([[SINAC]])\n}}\n\n'''Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge''' is a [[wildlife refuge]], part of the [[Tortuguero Conservation Area]], in [[Lim\u00f3n Province]] in the northeastern part of [[Costa Rica]]. It is the second largest [[rain forest]] preserve in the country and protects areas that contain hot [[humid forest]]s, [[mangrove]]s, [[canal]]s and [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] areas, bounded in part by the [[San Juan River (Nicaragua)|San Juan]] and [[Colorado River, Costa Rica|Colorado]] rivers, and to the south the [[Tortuguero National Park]].\n\nThe area protected has a hot and humid climate with no dry season, and is the habitat of the endangered [[West Indian manatee]] as well as many [[Caiman|caymans]], [[crocodile]]s, and fish. It is also home to a variety of [[tapir]]s, [[jaguar]]s, [[cougar]]s, [[monkey]]s, [[ocelot]]s, and other mammals. Birds found include [[osprey]], [[toucan]]s, [[cormorant]]s, [[heron]]s, [[hawk]]s, and many more.\n\nThe village of [[Tortuguero, Costa Rica|Tortuguero]] from which the neighbouring Tortuguero National Park got its name is located on the southern border the refuge, and contains two research stations.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929061404/http://www.acto.go.cr/bacolwildrefuge.html Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge, \u00c1rea de Conservaci\u00f3n Tortuguero]\n* [http://www.costarica-nationalparks.com/barradelcoloradowildliferefuge.html Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge] at Costa Rica National Parks\n\n[[Category:Nature reserves in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Geography of Lim\u00f3n Province]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-protected-area-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area \n| name = Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = Barra del Colorado Waterway.jpg\n| photo_caption =\n| location = [[Costa Rica]]\n| nearest_city = \n| coordinates = {{coords|10|46|18|N|83|35|56|W|display=inline, title}}\n| area = 200,600 acres (812 km\u00b2)\n| established = 1984\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = National System of Conservation Areas ([[SINAC]])\n}}\n\n'''Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge''' is a [[wildlife refuge]], part of the [[Tortuguero Conservation Area]], in [[Lim\u00f3n Province]] in the northeastern part of [[Costa Rica]]. It is the second largest [[rain forest]] preserve in the country and protects areas that contain hot [[humid forest]]s, [[mangrove]]s, [[canal]]s and [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] areas, bounded in part by the [[San Juan River (Nicaragua)|San Juan]] and [[Colorado River, Costa Rica|Colorado]] rivers, and to the south the [[Tortuguero National Park]].\n\nThe area protected has a hot and humid climate with no dry season, and is the habitat of the endangered [[West Indian manatee]] as well as many [[Caiman|caymans]], [[crocodile]]s, and fish. It is also home to a variety of [[tapir]]s, [[jaguar]]s, [[cougar]]s, [[monkey]]s, [[ocelot]]s, and other mammals. Birds found include [[osprey]], [[toucan]]s, [[cormorant]]s, [[heron]]s, [[hawk]]s, and many more.\n\nThe village of [[Tortuguero, Costa Rica|Tortuguero]] from which the neighbouring Tortuguero National Park got its name is located on the southern border the refuge, and contains two research stations.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070929061404/http://www.acto.go.cr/bacolwildrefuge.html Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge, \u00c1rea de Conservaci\u00f3n Tortuguero]\n* [http://www.costarica-nationalparks.com/barradelcoloradowildliferefuge.html Barra del Colorado Wildlife Refuge] at Costa Rica National Parks\n\n[[Category:Nature reserves in Costa Rica]]\n[[Category:Geography of Lim\u00f3n Province]]\n\n\n{{CostaRica-protected-area-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Roqz", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding map", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barra_del_Colorado_Wildlife_Refuge"}
{"title_page": "St\u00eanio Yamamoto", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = St\u00eanio Yamamoto\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = St\u00eanio Akiro Yamamoto\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = {{BRA}}\n| residence      =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|6|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.73|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|90|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Shooting sport|Shooting]]\n| event          =  10 m air pistol ([[AP60]])<br/>50 m pistol ([[50 metre pistol|FP]])\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          =\n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''St\u00eanio Akiro Yamamoto''' (born June 24, 1961 in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]) is a Brazilian sport shooter of Japanese descent.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|St\u00eanio Yamamoto|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ya/stenio-yamamoto-1.html|20 January 2013}}</ref> He won a silver medal in the free pistol at the [[2007 ISSF World Cup]] series in [[Munich, Germany]], with a score of 660.8 points.<ref name=issf>{{cite web|title=ISSF Profile \u2013 St\u00eanio Yamamoto|url=http://www.issf-sports.org/athletes/athlete.ashx?personissfid=SHBRAM2406196101|publisher=[[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]]|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Brasileiro Stenio Yamamoto \u00e9 prata em etapa da Copa do Mundo de tiro|trans-title=Brazilian shooter Stenio Yamamoto wins silver in World Cup|language=Portuguese|url=http://noticias.uol.com.br/ultnot/esporte/2007/06/01/ult1777u66507.jhtm|publisher=UOL Esporte|date=1 June 2007|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt age forty-seven, Yamamoto made his official debut for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], where he competed in two pistol shooting events. He scored a total of 568 targets in the preliminary rounds of the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Men's 10 metre air pistol|men's 10 m air pistol]], by one point ahead of Romania's [[Iulian Raicea]], finishing only in forty-third place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's 10m Air Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHM203901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |access-date=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816053200/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHM203901/index.html |archive-date=16 August 2012 |df= }}</ref> Three days later, Yamamoto placed forty-fourth in his second event, [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Men's 50 metre pistol|50 m pistol]], by two points behind Tajikistan's [[Sergey Babikov]], with a total score of 538 targets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's 50m Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHM201901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |access-date=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816054005/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHM201901/index.html |archive-date=16 August 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://olimpiadas.uol.com.br/2008/atletas-brasileiros/tiro-esportivo/stenio-yamamoto.jhtm Profile \u2013 UOL Esporte] {{in lang|pt}}\n*[http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/athletes/athlete=62781/bio/index.html NBC 2008 Olympics profile] {{dead link|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yamamoto, Stenio}}\n[[Category:Brazilian male sport shooters]]\n[[Category:Brazilian people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Olympic shooters of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games competitors for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Shooters at the 2003 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-sportshooting-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor = lightblue\n| name           = St\u00eanio Yamamoto\n| image          = \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_name     = \n| fullname       = St\u00eanio Akiro Yamamoto\n| nickname       =\n| nationality    = {{BRA}}\n| residence      =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|6|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = {{height|m=1.73|abbr=on}}\n| weight         = {{convert|90|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| website        = \n| country        = \n| sport          = [[Shooting sport|Shooting]]\n| event          =  10 m air pistol ([[AP60]])<br/>50 m pistol ([[50 metre pistol|FP]])\n| collegeteam    = \n| club           = \n| turnedpro      = \n| coach          =\n| retired        = \n| coaching       = \n| worlds         = \n| regionals      = \n| nationals      = \n| olympics       = \n| paralympics    = \n| highestranking = \n| pb             = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = yes\n}}\n\n'''St\u00eanio Akiro Yamamoto''' (born June 24, 1961 in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]) is a Brazilian sport shooter of Japanese descent.<ref>{{cite sports-reference|St\u00eanio Yamamoto|https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ya/stenio-yamamoto-1.html|20 January 2013}}</ref> He won a silver medal in the free pistol at the [[2007 ISSF World Cup]] series in [[Munich, Germany]], with a score of 660.8 points.<ref name=issf>{{cite web|title=ISSF Profile \u2013 St\u00eanio Yamamoto|url=http://www.issf-sports.org/athletes/athlete.ashx?personissfid=SHBRAM2406196101|publisher=[[International Shooting Sport Federation|ISSF]]|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Brasileiro Stenio Yamamoto \u00e9 prata em etapa da Copa do Mundo de tiro|trans-title=Brazilian shooter Stenio Yamamoto wins silver in World Cup|language=Portuguese|url=http://noticias.uol.com.br/ultnot/esporte/2007/06/01/ult1777u66507.jhtm|publisher=UOL Esporte|date=1 June 2007|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt age forty-seven, Yamamoto made his official debut for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in [[Beijing]], where he competed in two pistol shooting events. He scored a total of 568 targets in the preliminary rounds of the [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Men's 10 metre air pistol|men's 10 m air pistol]], by one point ahead of Romania's [[Iulian Raicea]], finishing only in forty-third place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's 10m Air Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHM203901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |access-date=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816053200/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHM203901/index.html |archive-date=16 August 2012 |df= }}</ref> Three days later, Yamamoto placed forty-fourth in his second event, [[Shooting at the 2008 Summer Olympics - Men's 50 metre pistol|50 m pistol]], by two points behind Tajikistan's [[Sergey Babikov]], with a total score of 538 targets.<ref>{{cite web|title=Men's 50m Pistol Qualification |url=http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc=SHM201901/index.html |publisher=[[NBC Olympics]] |access-date=20 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816054005/http://www.2008.nbcolympics.com/shooting/resultsandschedules/rsc%3DSHM201901/index.html |archive-date=16 August 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://olimpiadas.uol.com.br/2008/atletas-brasileiros/tiro-esportivo/stenio-yamamoto.jhtm Profile \u2013 UOL Esporte] {{i